Wezloc <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ukinelaria.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Kinelaria</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Master Summoner</span><br>  Posts: 215<br> <font color=#333333>(5/24/02 7:37:41 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=210.topic&index=17>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   ...</span><hr size=1> I think alot of our problems stem from a breakdown in EQ's method of class dynamics. EQ classes were intended to be interdependant on one another and this breaks down in the case of magicians (other classes too, but I'll stick to issues I can attest to). Enchanters are dependant on other classes to deal damage and keep the mobs at bay, in turn others depend on enchanters to increase their melee output (haste), casting abilities (numerous chanter mind buffs), crowd control, and various other little functions. Clerics of course rely on others for the same things enchanters do, and others rely on the cleric to provide buffs and healing. Magicians on the other hand rely on others a great deal and can bring little more than damage output, mod rods are really a luxury item for xp  groups and can be lived without. While our damage output is hardly crap, we cannot sustain it for terribly long. Monks and rogues can do pretty close to, if not exceeding our damage output and have no downtime, thus the death  of casters being ranked as damage dealers in a group. I fault the design team for not placing ceilings on how good weapons could get, it has lead to a huge escalation in power and seems bound to continue unchecked.<br>
<br>
As for the monster summonings, I think I'd like something a little differant. While I like the idea of summoning a &quot;real&quot; monster, it sounds a wee bit limiting to me. Instead I think I'd like to see something like:<br>
- Melee damage appropriate to the spell circle it is in<br>
- Base HP, AC, and stats modelled off the earth pet as it is now<br>
- Rather than summoning an elemental in disguise, summon a pet with a random mob type:<br>
*Shaman, lower HP and AC, casts slows, disease/poison dot's, sow's other pets in the group, casts cold DD's<br>
*Cleric, lower HP and AC, heals itself and other pets, casts cleric DD's and perhaps stuns<br>
*Warrior, higher HP and AC but otherwise same<br>
*Monk, lower HP higher melee damage, blocks and does more kick damage, higher level ones tripple attack<br>
*Rogue, lower hp and ac, can backstab if behind the mob<br>
<br>
Well you get the idea. The advantage would be getting to summon a pet with abilities our elementals do not have, the downside of course is you won't know what you have till you fight with it. Then of course getting the pet type you want as well as one that is at the level you need/want. If needed they could also make the monster summons unhealable by use of our pet heals (since they're monsters not elementals). I do think they should wear armor and wield weapons though (even if they cannot be displayed). Though perhaps the casting types couldn't dual wield, assuming it's possible to make that exception without breaking everything else.<br>
<br>
Kinelaria<br>
